<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="95" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="95">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="95">Mentum without foveae; labrum bilobed, covering mandibles; head with single pair of supraorbital setae; elytra truncate; terminal abdominal ventrite of both male and female with four long setae, the lateral pair sickle-shaped. ABL = 1.2-3.0 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="95" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="95">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="95">
Often abundant at lights, this speciose and underdescribed genus is known from southern North America to northern South America and the Caribbean (
<bibRefCitation author="Erwin, TL" journalOrPublisher="Revista Peruana de Entomologia" pageId="30" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 85" title="Natural history of the carabid beetles at the BIOLAT Biological Station, Rio Manu, Pakitza, Peru." volume="33" year="1991">Erwin 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Erwin, TL" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences" pageId="31" pageNumber="118" title="The Family Carabidae: Key to the Tribes and Genera known to occur in Costa Rica" url="http://www.inbio.ac.cr/papers/carabidae/esp/images/CR_carabid_key.doc" year="2002">Erwin et al. 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
